Package cmpt355.project.ast

Class QualifiedIdentifier

java.lang.Object
cmpt355.project.ast.QualifiedIdentifier
public final class QualifiedIdentifier
extends Object
Class representing a qualified identifier, that is, one or more identifiers separated by dots.

      public QualifiedIdentifier​(List<String> names)

    • QualifiedIdentifier

      public QualifiedIdentifier​(String... names)
      Constructs a new QualifiedIdentifier from one or more strings, for example 
      new QualifiedIdentifier("java", "util", "Scanner")
      for java.util.Scanner.
      Throws:
      IllegalArgumentException - if no names are furnished

  • Method Details

    • from

      public static QualifiedIdentifier from​(String source)
      Constructs a new QualifiedIdentifier from a string of dot-separated identifiers. For example, QualifiedIdentifier.from("java.util.Scanner") has the same effect as new QualifiedIdentifier("java", "util", "Scanner").
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if source is null

    • from

      public static QualifiedIdentifier from​(List<org.antlr.v4.runtime.Token> tokens)

    • length

      public int length()
      Returns the length of this QualifiedIdentifier, i.e., how many identifiers it contains. This will always be at least 1.

    • head

      public String head()
      Returns the first name in this QualifiedIdentifier (for x.y.z, returns x). Whenever qi is a QualifiedIdentifier and qi.length() > 1, it is true that qi.head().appending(qi.tail()) is equal to qi.
      See Also:
      tail()

    • head

      public QualifiedIdentifier head​(int count)
      Returns a QualifiedIdentifier of the first n names (for x.y.z, .head(2) returns x.y). Whenever qi is a QualifiedIdentifier and 1 < n < qi.length(), it is true that qi.head(n).appending(qi.tail(n)) is equal to qi.
      Throws:
      IllegalArgumentException - if count is less than 1 or greater than the number of names
      See Also:
      tail(int)

    • tail

      public QualifiedIdentifier tail()
      Returns the tail of this QualifiedIdentifier after the head is removed, that is, all names but the first (for x.y.z, returns y.z). Whenever qi is a QualifiedIdentifier and qi.length() > 1, it is true that qi.head().appending(qi.tail()) is equal to qi.
      Throws:
      IllegalStateException - if there is only one name
      See Also:
      head()

    • tail

      public QualifiedIdentifier tail​(int count)
      Returns the tail of this QualifiedIdentifier after the head of count names is removed (for x.y.z, .tail(2) returns z). Whenever qi is a QualifiedIdentifier and 1 < n < qi.length(), it is true that qi.head(n).appending(qi.tail(n)) is equal to qi.
      Throws:
      IllegalArgumentException - if count < 0 or count ≥ this.length()

    • last

      public String last()
      Returns the last name (identifier) in this QualifiedIdentifier (for x.y.z, returns the string z).

    • appending

      public QualifiedIdentifier appending​(QualifiedIdentifier id)
      Returns a new QualifiedIdentifier composed of all names of this identifier followed by all those of id. If qi1 is a.b.c and qi2 is x.y, the result is a.b.c.x.y.
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if id is null

    • appending

      public QualifiedIdentifier appending​(String name)
      Returns new QualifiedIdentifier obtained by adding a single additional name to this one. If qi is a.b.c, then qi.appending("onetwothree" is a.b.c.onetwothree.
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if name is null

    • hashCode

      public int hashCode()
      Overrides:
      hashCode in class Object

    • equals

      public boolean equals​(Object obj)
      Overrides:
      equals in class Object

    • toString

      public String toString()
      Returns the string obtained by joining the names together with dots between them (i.e. new QualifiedIdentifier("java", "util", "Scanner").toString() returns "java.util.Scanner".
      Overrides:
      toString in class Object

    • toJvmString

      public String toJvmString()
      Returns the string obtained by joining the names together with forward slashes between them (i.e. new QualifiedIdentifier("java", "util", "Scanner").toString() returns "java/util/Scanner".
